      "side": 1,
      "message": "Hi Adrien, could you please take another look at this change in light of the completed investigation and hardware campaign?\n\nYour point about observable write failures was correct; that path is handled separately by dhtnet 34875. Change 34845 addresses a distinct reproduced case: the ChannelRequest write returns the full byte count with no error, but no ACCEPT or DECLINE arrives. In the deterministic dhtnet test, the mux stayed active, TX was credited, the callback never ran, and `isConnecting(device, name)` remained true. With the 3 s mux-liveness deadline, the silent mux closed and the retry completed exactly once on a different socket. PS2 uses the existing public `SEND_BEACON_TIMEOUT` policy rather than a hard-coded daemon duration.\n\nWe then ran the R1-R5 Mac-to-iPad hardware campaign with 34845 PS2 as the unchanged base and identified three additional wake/delivery issues, now addressed by 34900, 34901, and the iOS client change 34902. The stale-channel cycle reproduced spontaneously three times; recovery delivered in 7.1, 2.2, and 1.8 seconds, versus about 12 minutes before the fix. Offline aggregation and the single re-announce were verified with three puts for three messages and no put storm. In the foreground airplane-mode scenario, the previous behavior left messages undelivered for 25 minutes and dropped 11 valid answers across four orphan windows; the bounded series in 34901 delivered 1.5 seconds after network return. The live +210 s answer was accepted, the Mac-initiated channel opened, and later retries were cancelled.\n\nThe client-side foreground connectivity issue found during the same campaign is isolated in 34902. I would appreciate a re-review of 34845 and the stacked follow-ups with these new reproductions and measurements in mind.",
