      "writtenOn": "2026-07-14T21:10:17Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "Thanks for raising the coupling concern. In the exact dhtnet revision used here, `SEND_BEACON_TIMEOUT` is not a DHT beacon interval; it is the public 3000 ms response deadline for the multiplexed socket\u0027s liveness beacon. Reusing that duration is intentional: `MessageChannelHandler::onRequest` only validates the certificate and returns synchronously, so there is no normal application-level latency that would justify a separate message-channel policy. If a locally accepted ChannelRequest receives neither ACCEPT nor DECLINE within the mux liveness window, the control path on that mux is no longer useful for this operation.\n\nA daemon-local 3000 ms constant would duplicate the same policy and could drift from dhtnet. The deterministic dhtnet reproduction also confirmed the intended behavior: without the deadline, the mux remained active, TX was credited, the callback never ran, and `isConnecting(device, name)` stayed true; with the 3 s deadline, the silent mux closed and the retry completed once on a different socket.\n\nThe follow-up wake/delivery handling is now in 34900 and 34901. Hardware validation recovered repeated zombie-channel cases in 2.2 and 1.8 s (7.1 s on the first occurrence), versus about 12 minutes before the fix, and recovered the airplane-mode orphan window in 1.5 s versus 25 minutes, without a put storm.",
      "parentUuid": "03c78be3_547929fe",
      "revId": "8c656b5194a9538eb7d8892b51ea552857307fb3",
      "serverId": "1e26b4c1-6b8c-47ff-9df7-501b633d3b5a"
