      "writtenOn": "2026-07-14T21:10:17Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "Confirmed: expiry calls `MultiplexedSocket::shutdown()`, so every channel on that mux is closed. This is an intentional trade-off with the current dhtnet API. There is no public per-channel cancellation that both removes the pending ConnectionManager operation, completes its callback, and allows the retry to move to a new socket.\n\nFor this handler, a healthy mux should answer immediately: `MessageChannelHandler::onRequest` performs only certificate validation and returns synchronously. Receiving neither ACCEPT nor DECLINE therefore means that the mux control path is silent; keeping application channels attached to that transport would preserve a connection that cannot complete new channel negotiation. Closing it completes the pending operation with a null channel and lets the retry negotiate a fresh socket.\n\nThe deterministic reproduction exercised this exact silent-control-path case. The R1-R5 hardware campaign then validated the surrounding recovery in 34900/34901: repeated stale-channel failures recovered in seconds rather than 12 minutes, airplane-mode recovery completed 1.5 s after network return rather than remaining undelivered for 25 minutes, aggregation was preserved, and no channel or push storm occurred. We did not exercise the timeout while an active call shared the mux, so I am not claiming direct coverage of that collateral case; the rationale here is the absence of a usable per-channel recovery primitive and the synchronous reply contract.",
